South Africa&#8217;s rand fell nearly 2 percent on Tuesday, extending its losing streak into a seventh straight session a day after S&amp;P Global Ratings cut the country&#8217;s credit rating to sub-investment grade with a negative outlook.At 8:20 am, the rand traded at 13.8578 per dollar, 1.8% weaker from its Monday close.S&amp;P cut the credit rating to BB+ from BBB- and assigned a negative outlook, citing fiscal policy risk following Pravin Gordhan&#8217;s sacking as finance minister.Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba to brief media on S&amp;P downgrade at 9:30 a.m. (0730 GMT)Moody&#8217;s also places South Africa&#8217;s credit rating on review.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 21 basis points to 9.19%.